06056nam a22008775i 9783110561197DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20172017gw     fo  d z      lat d  a97831105611977 a10.1515/97831105611972doi  a(DE-B1597)487357  a(OCoLC)1024028046  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 alat  agwcDE 7aREL0670802bisacsh1 aMelanchthon, Philipp, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOpera omnia. pSchriften zur Dialektik und Rhetorik. nPart 2. pPrincipal Writings on Rhetoric /cWilliam P. Weaver, Stefan Strohm, Volkhard Wels. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (LIV, 594 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOpera omnia00tFrontmatter -- tInhaltsverzeichnis / Table of Contents -- tZur Edition der „Melanchthonis opera philosophica“ -- tVolume Introduction -- tDe Rhetorica Libri Tres -- tEditorischer Bericht -- tEdition -- tAnhang -- tInstitutiones Rhetoricae -- tEditorial Report -- tInstitutiones Rhetoricae Philippi Melanchthonis -- tElementa Rhetorices -- tEditorischer Bericht -- tElementorum Rhetorices Libri Duo -- tDispositiones Aliquot Rhetoricae -- tEditorial Report -- tMelanchthons Dispositiones rhetoricae vom Jahre 1553 -- tDispositiones aliquot rhetoricae dictatae a Domino Philippo Melanthone Vitebergae -- tIndexes -- tIndex of Bible Citations -- tIndex of Citations -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Terms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe need for a new critical edition of Philip Melanchthon's philosophical works is particularly clear in the case of his writings on rhetoric. That Melanchthon played a central role in the transformation of the ancient discipline has been well established by historians. His writings on rhetoric have proven significant sources for several academic fields, including church history, Scriptural interpretation, the history of science, and the reception of classical literature. Remarkably, two of the three principal writings have not been published in their entirety since the sixteenth century. This volume collects critical editions of the three principal writings to provide a more complete record of Melanchthon’s teaching of rhetoric. It includes critical editions of De Rhetorica (1519), Institutiones Rhetoricae (1521), and Elementa Rhetorices (1531). In addition to the three principal writings, this volume collects a new edition, based on a 1911 edition by Hanns Zwicker, of Dispositiones Rhetoricae (c. 1553), a manuscript compilation of 161 model themes. Scholars will find in this volume the major sources for Melanchthon’s theory and practice of rhetorical instruction.  aThis volume collects for the first time critical editions of Melanchthon’s three principal writings on rhetoric. These writings were instrumental in the transformation of the liberal arts and the development of Protestant hermeneutics, preaching, and teaching in the era of Renaissance and Reformation. The volume includes the first critical editions of two of these writings and a revised critical edition of the third.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Latin.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 4aDialektik. 4aReformation. 4aRenaissance. 4aRhetorik. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aDialectic.  aReformation.  aRenaissance.  aRhetoric.1 aSchmid, Hartmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrohm, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrohm, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeaver, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeaver, William P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt